Forgot to add this for the novice writers.
If you're branching from an established property, and doubly so if you're using established characters, please leave enough room that I don't need get a PhD in that property's lore.
Write as though you're doing Book Ten of a longrunning series.
Explain just enough that the unfamiliar can follow your plot. Retain enough lore that a fan gets bonuses. Treat the characters well, and you'll be better off than most.

Anonymous Fri 03 Apr 2020 01:32:51 No.29370553 Report
Quoted By: >>29370678
>>29370327
Short of it, move on and let the next scene help you.

I've written sex scenes that were almost 4k words, and had that finished in a night.
I've had simple description that took a week to get 1000 words.

Don't get too wrapped up in perfect. You can't predict what's going to be easy for you. I tend to write dialogue first, then go back and add tags. After that I fill in exposition or setting as needed. Yet I've gotten stumped on all of those elements.
Important is relative. In good writing every scene is important. If it wasn't, you could cut the subordinate scenes and lose nothing of the plot or characterization.

Anonymous Fri 03 Apr 2020 02:44:41 No.29371847 Report
Quoted By:
>>29371299
For future reference, divide the byte count by six for a word count approximation.

In all honesty it has that first draft feel to me. Granted, I revise and edit greentext to hell and back.
Green is OK for short material, but one bugaboos is starting a new line for every clause in a sentence. Great for outlining, bad for readability.
Since NEP mostly avoided that, one can excuse most of the other potential issues. It's far better to underuse a thesaurus if your own vocabulary has a low word count than go purple.
As far as structure, it's a good example of why second person is harder to pull off. The perspective is less familiar to readers; it's usually more wordy than first or third to describe the same action.

While I agree it's nothing to write home about, we need material like this. Shorts with earthy flaws allow new Anons to say that's achievable. Writers have to start somewhere.

Are you the guy trying to write for the first time?
Find music you really like and imagine it's soundtracking a scene. Write to the music. When it crescendos, you must also let that whip you up into a writing frenzy. When it wanes maybe that's your cue to bring the scene down in emotional intensity and whatnot.

For example, I wrote a few scenes to this album https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xe7SOq1Yy2o but pick any song/album you like

Really, the trick isn't so much to write as it is to feel and express it, even if it's incoherent. You can fix that in post
